theorem
((M1 is  invertible & ( M1 * M2 ) = ( 1. (K,n) )) implies M1 is_reverse_of M2)
proof
A1: (( width M1 ) = n & ( len M1 ) = n) by MATRIX_1:24;
A2: (( len M2 ) = n & ( width ( M1 ~ ) ) = n) by MATRIX_1:24;
assume that
A3: M1 is  invertible
and
A4: ( M1 * M2 ) = ( 1. (K,n) );
A5: ( M1 ~ ) is_reverse_of M1 by A3,CKB15:def 1;
( ( M1 ~ ) * ( M1 * M2 ) ) = ( M1 ~ ) by A4,MATRIX_3:19;
then ( ( ( M1 ~ ) * M1 ) * M2 ) = ( M1 ~ ) by A1,A2,MATRIX_3:33;
then ( ( 1. (K,n) ) * M2 ) = ( M1 ~ ) by A5,CKB2:def 1;
then M2 = ( M1 ~ ) by MATRIX_3:18;
hence thesis by A3,CKB15:def 1;
end;
